               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18280221-283-off1494-c1578" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-283-defend1582 t18280221-283-off1494 t18280221-283-verdict1497"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18280221-283-off1494-c1579" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-283-defend1583 t18280221-283-off1494 t18280221-283-verdict1499"></join>
         
               <p>Fourth Middlesex Jury - before Mr. Common Sergeant.</p>
               <p>761. 
               <persName id="t18280221-283-defend1582" type="defendantName">
                  JAMES 
                  GARRARD
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-defend1582" type="surname" value="GARRARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-defend1582" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-defend1582" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-defend1582" type="age" value="18"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and 
               <persName id="t18280221-283-defend1583" type="defendantName">
                  ANDREW 
                  KEATING
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-defend1583" type="surname" value="KEATING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-defend1583" type="given" value="ANDREW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-defend1583" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-defend1583" type="age" value="17"></interp>
                  </persName>
             were indicted for <rs id="t18280221-283-off1494" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-off1494" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-off1494" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18280221-283-cd1495" type="crimeDate">11th of January</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-283-off1494 t18280221-283-cd1495"></join>, 26lbs. weight of Sugar, value 14s.
            </rs>, the goods of 
               <persName id="t18280221-283-victim1584" type="victimName">
                  William 
                  Sewell
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-victim1584" type="surname" value="Sewell"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-victim1584" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-victim1584" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and 
               <persName id="t18280221-283-victim1585" type="victimName">
                  Jonathan 
                  Wholey
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-victim1585" type="surname" value="Wholey"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-victim1585" type="given" value="Jonathan"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-victim1585" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-283-person1586">
                  EDWARD 
                  BARKER
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1586" type="surname" value="BARKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1586" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1586" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am warehousemen to William Sewell and Jonathan Wholey, <rs id="t18280221-283-viclabel1496" type="occupation">wholesale grocers</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-283-victim1584 t18280221-283-viclabel1496"></join>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-283-victim1585 t18280221-283-viclabel1496"></join>, of Upper Thames-street. I forwarded a hogshead of sugar to Mr. Beal, of Somers-town, on the 11th of January: it was brought from the Docks to our warehouse by Garrard, who is in the employ of a carman named Kay: I directed him to take it on to Beal's - this was about three o'clock in the afternoon; I examined the marks on it, and took the weight from the dock note - I knew nothing of Keating.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. You did not examine it? A. I took the marks of it down as it was in the cart.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-283-person1587">
                  WILLIAM 
                  BOOTH
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1587" type="surname" value="BOOTH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1587" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1587" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a chemist. Between five and six o'clock on the 11th of January; I was going along Battle Bridge-road - it snowed; I met the prisoners there- they could not get on with the waggon; I and some others assisted them - Keating got into the waggon between two hogsheads, which were in it: they got as far as Weston-street, and there they staid some time; we found fault with Garrard for using his horses so badly, - I then walked round the waggon, and Keating jumped out - thinking something was wrong, I pursued and took him; he said, "Pray let me go," and asked for his hat.</p>
               <p>Prisoner KEATING. Q. Did I not ask you where Garrard was? A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-283-person1588">
                  MILLIAM 
                  LUMLEY
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1588" type="surname" value="LUMLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1588" type="given" value="MILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1588" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Cottage-place, City-road. I saw the waggon - Booth was talking to Garrard about whipping his horses so much; I caught hold of the horses head, and then Booth went back, and was talking under a light to a man who I could not see; Garrard then came up to me, used very bad language, and said, "What, did you never see a waggon with two horses before:" I then thought I saw something move in the waggon under the matting - I touched it with my umbrella, and Keating jumped out; we caught him, and he was taken to the watch-house: Beal came up and said, "This is my sugar, and was coming to my house" - the hogsheads were then taken to his house, and it was found 26 lbs. had been taken out of one - a few nails were found on Keating; he said he lived in the Commercial-road - there was a bag of sugar - I saw it at Mr. Beal's; I think I saw a man bring it from the waggon, but I cannot swear that - it was opened, and contained sugar, which Beale compared with the hogshead.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Was it dark? A. Not very - there were gas-lights; I do not think it snowed at that time; I think I did see the bag taken from the cart - I may have sworn so at the office.</p>
               <p>Prisoner KEATING. Q. Did I not tell you Garrard had told me to get up and fill the bag? A. He said as we went to the watch-house, that the carman asked him to come and get a little sugar.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-283-person1589">
                  THOMAS 
                  BEAL
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1589" type="surname" value="BEAL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1589" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1589" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a grocer, and live in Skinner-street, St. Pancras. I expected two hogsheads of sugar on the 11th of January, from the prosecutors - one came in the morning; about seven o'clock I had information - I went to Brewer-street, and saw Booth bringing Keating back; I went up to the waggon, and between two hogsheads of sugar, I found a bag of sugar, and some was coming out of the hogshead into the bag then; the tin plate which covered the sample-hole, was knocked off, and twisted round - it hung by one nail; the waggon was brought to my house, and the hogshead and the bag brought in; the sugar in the bag was the same as that in the hogshead; I weighed the hogshead, and it was 26lbs. deficient.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CHURCHILL. Q. What is over the sample-hole? A. A piece of tin nailed on; it could not have got rubbed off - a chisel or a knife will get it off.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-283-person1590">
                  RICHARD 
                  COOPER
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1590" type="surname" value="COOPER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1590" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1590" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable, and took Keating in charge. I found a few nails on him - they are not the same sort as the one left in the tin.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-283-person1591">
                  ROBERT 
                  TEASDALE
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1591" type="surname" value="TEASDALE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1591" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1591" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I produce a bag of sugar, which I received from Mr. Beal; I saw the hogshead weighed - I was before the Magistrate - what the prisoners said was taken down, and read over to them; Garrard said he met Keating in Gray's Inn-lane.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-283-person1592">
                  THOMAS 
                  BEAL
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1592" type="surname" value="BEAL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1592" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1592" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The nails found on Keating would nail the tin on - it is done with any kind of nails; there was a chasm in the sample-hole; I have no doubt the sugar in the bag was the same as that in the hogshead - part of it was running out when I took it.</p>
               <p>MR. CHURCHILL. Q. If the plate had come off by accident, could they do better than put the bag to catch it? A. No; but that quantity could not have come out of itself; the proper way would be to turn the hole to the top.</p>
               <p>KEATING'S Defence. I met Garrard in Gray's Inn-lane- he could not get on: the sugar was running out - he told me to get up and get a little out, in a bag; I picked up the nails on Galley-quay.</p>
               <p>GARRARD'S Defence. I met him, and said I would give him a pint of beer to go with me; the tin had robbed off, by rubbing against the other hogshead - I had a bag, and told him to get in and catch it; the tin was nearly off when I had it.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182802210139"></xptr>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-283-person1593">
                  JOHN 
                  HALL
               <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1593" type="surname" value="HALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1593" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-person1593" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a publican. I have known Garrard all his life; I have worked in the docks as an operative cooper, and have frequently seen sugar wasting in the Commercial-road; from the friction of two hogsheads together; the tin, being nailed in the bulge, might very possibly rub off; I have known the tin actually worn through.</p>
               <p>Garrard received a good character.</p>
               <p>GARRARD - <rs id="t18280221-283-verdict1497" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18280221-283-verdict1497" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 18.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280221-283-punish1498" type="punishmentDescription">
